{
  "answer": "In the Old English elegy *The Wanderer*, the compound *goldwine* (\"gold-friend,\" denoting a generous lord who bestows gold treasures on his retainers) evokes the warmth of lost patronage and social bonds: \"since long ago my **gold-friend** / the earth's darkness covered.\"[^1]\n\nIn Allama Iqbal's Urdu poem \"Mehr-e-roshan\" (\"The Shining Sun\"), the polysemous *mehr* (sun, but also kindness/affection/sun-like generosity) opens with solar imagery of setting warmth: \"**Mehr-e-roshan** chhip gaya\" (\"The shining sun has gone from sight\").[^2]\n\nDoes the \"warmth\" in each—material/economic bonds via gifts (*goldwine*) versus radiant affection or natural light (*mehr*)—stem from the same metaphorical place, or something culturally distinct?\n\n[^1]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/32-mehr-e-roshan/transliteration/#p-6d3166).",
